<button class="accordion">What is the meaning of duty of candour?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Duty of candour is a statutory duty that emphasises the need to be open and honest with patients or service users and their families, particularly when something goes wrong and may lead to significant harm in the future.
</p>
<p>The Mandatory Training Group is the leading UK provider of accredited statutory and mandatory training courses for all sectors, including health, safety and wellbeing, social care, education, local government, and many more.<a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/products/statutory-duty-of-candour-online-training-course-cpduk-accredited?variant=29110107766818"_blank""><font color="green"><u> Click here for Online Duty of Candour Training Course.</u></font></a></p><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is the duty of candour training a legal requirement?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Yes, the duty of candour is a legal requirement. The CQC will be able to take enforcement action when it finds breaches.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What does the duty of candour mean in law?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>In UK public law, the duty of candour is the duty imposed on a public authority 'not to seek to win litigation at all costs but to assist the court in reaching the correct result and thereby to improve standards in public administration'.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is the duty of candour essential?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The UK government's decision to make the duty of candour a legal requirement for organisations sends a clear message of expectation to health and social care providers. It requires an organisation to embrace a commitment to safety fully, learning lessons and ultimately improving care as a result.
</p>
<p>The Mandatory Training Group is the leading UK provider of accredited statutory and mandatory training courses for all sectors, including health, safety and wellbeing, social care, education, local government, and many more.<a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/products/statutory-duty-of-candour-online-training-course-cpduk-accredited?variant=29110107766818"_blank""><font color="green"><u> Click here for Online Duty of Candour Training Course.</u></font></a></p><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What triggered the statutory duty of candour?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The contractual duty of candour is triggered by individual patient safety incidents that result in moderate or severe harm or death.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">When was the duty of candour introduced?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The statutory duty was introduced in November 2014 for NHS bodies such as trusts and foundation trusts in England. It was extended in April 2015 to cover all registered care providers.
</p> 
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the duty of candour in the NHS?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The new duty of candour on organisations creates a legal requirement for health and social care organisations to inform patients, as well as their families/carers, when they have been physically or psychologically harmed as a result of the care or treatment they have received.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What must healthcare professionals do to comply with the duty of candour?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Every healthcare professional must be open and honest with patients when something goes wrong with their treatment or care that causes or has the potential to cause, harm or distress. This means that healthcare professionals must:
</p>
<li>Tell the patient (or the patient's advocate, carer or family) when something has gone wrong</li>
<li>Apologise to the patient (or the patient's advocate, carer or family)
</li>
<li>If possible, offer an appropriate remedy or support to put matters right
</li>
<li>Explain fully to the patient, their advocate, carer or family, the short and long term effects of what has happened.</li>
<p>Healthcare professionals must also be open and honest with their colleagues, employers and relevant organisations. They must also take part in reviews and investigations when requested. Moreover, they must be open and honest with their regulators and raise concerns where appropriate.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is this duty of candour training course essential?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>This duty of candour training course is essential as it conforms with Regulation 20 of the Health and Social Care Act 2008 (Regulated Activities) Regulations 2014. The regulation intends to ensure that providers are open and transparent concerning care and treatment with people who use their services.
</p>
<p>Furthermore, the CQC can prosecute for a breach of parts 20(2) and a 20(3) of this regulation.
